<subSubSection pageId="36" pageNumber="37" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="36.[189,310,1410,1436]" box="[189,310,1410,1436]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,310,1410,1436]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,310,1410,1436]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="36.[189,1399,1457,1589]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1848" box="[189,328,1457,1483]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Sertulariidae" genus="Sertularella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[189,328,1457,1483]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Sertularella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with lightly fascicled, irregularly and sparsely branched stems; internodes moderately long, geniculate; hydrothecae exceedingly long, gradually narrowing slightly from base to aperture, adnate for ¼ or less, free adaxial side with 7–9 transverse ridges, an intrathecal cusp abaxially. Gonothecae unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="36" pageNumber="37" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="36.[189,324,1628,1654]" box="[189,324,1628,1654]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,324,1628,1654]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,324,1628,1654]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Etymology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="36.[189,1399,1675,1772]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">
From the Latin adjective 
<emphasis box="[511,625,1675,1701]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">splendĭdo</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis box="[647,671,1676,1701]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">-a</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis box="[692,876,1675,1701]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">-um (splendeo)</emphasis>
, originally meaning brilliant, dazzling, or glowing, but subsequently retained as “splendid” or “magnificent” in modern usage, to denote the beautiful appearance displayed by this species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
